[1] Wilt, berry disease - Ethiopia
Date: 19 Dec 2008
Source: Bloomberg [edited]
<http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601116&sid=auYwM6dFzZlI&refer=africa>


Ethiopian coffee output slides 58 percent in 2 main growing regions
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Ethiopian coffee output will fall 58 percent in 2 of the country's
main growing regions this year because of disease and a lack of
water, the government said. Output in Sidama region fell as much as
55 percent and Gedeo by 62 percent, Berhanu Gezahegn, an official at
the agriculture ministry's coffee development office, said. The areas
in southern Ethiopia produce about 60 percent of Ethiopia's
high-quality washed coffee and are home to the Yirgacheffe and Sidama
varieties.

"There's a big reduction in washed coffee," Gezahegn said. "There was
a moisture shortage in the 3rd flowering and a big infestation of
coffee berry disease and coffee wilt disease." Washed coffee makes up
70 to 75 percent of the production in the 2 regions, while lower
quality dried coffee accounts for the remainder, he said. A drought
from March to June [2008] harmed coffee flowering in the region, he
said. "In August and September there was a big rain and that rain
caused" coffee berry disease, he added.

A U.N. report warned that the drop in production combined with lower
world coffee prices and higher food prices were leading to widespread
malnutrition in the regions.

[Byline: Jason McLure]

